  "response_text": "The average weekly consumption of whole milk per agent begins at approximately 2600 units during the initial time steps. A significant decline occurs between steps 2 and 10, where consumption drops to around 1000 units. This sharp decrease suggests a strong shift in consumer preferences away from whole milk during this period. From steps 10 to 20, the decline continues but at a slower rate, reaching about 800 units. This indicates a gradual transition as consumers increasingly adopt alternative milk types. Between steps 20 and 25, the reduction becomes more moderate, stabilizing around 700 units. A more pronounced drop is observed between steps 26 and 28, bringing consumption down to approximately 400 units. This may reflect a tipping point where social influence and health perceptions further accelerate the shift. Finally, from step 29 onwards, consumption stabilizes at around 300 units, showing little variation. This suggests a new equilibrium has been reached where the majority of consumers have transitioned to skimmed or semi-skimmed milk. Decision-makers can infer that health-related perceptions and social dynamics are critical drivers in altering long-standing consumption habits."
}

